            l, r = left.pop(), right.pop(0)
            if pos_health[l][0] < pos_health[r][0]:
                ans.append(pos_health[l])
            elif pos_health[l][0] > pos_health[r][0]:
                ans.append(pos_health[r])
            else:
                if pos_health[l][1] < pos_health[r][1]:
                    pos_health[r] = (pos_health[r][0], pos_health[r][1] - 1)
                    ans.append(pos_health[r]) 
                elif pos_health[l][1] > pos_health[r][1]:
                    pos_health[l] = (pos_health[l][0], pos_health[l][1] - 1)
                    ans.append(pos_health[l])
                else:
                    continue

        return [h for p, h in ans]
```

The key ideas are:

- Sort positions and healths together so we can compare them easily.
- Use two pointers for left and right robots.
- Simulate collisions by comparing positions. Update healths accordingly.
- Return only the final healths in order.

This runs in O(nlogn) time due to sorting and O(n) space.

